        <td id="LC266" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">&lt;<span class="pl-ent">p</span>&gt;Here we get more than we thought, including everything after the first quotation mark.What happened? Because the &lt;<span class="pl-ent">code</span>&gt;+&lt;/<span class="pl-ent">code</span>&gt; is greedy, it matched as much as it could following the first quote, including the following quotation mark and everything else in the string. Why, then was the final “…” excluded? The &lt;<span class="pl-ent">code</span>&gt;.+&lt;/<span class="pl-ent">code</span>&gt; combo kept matching until it reached the end of the string where the &lt;<span class="pl-ent">code</span>&gt;.&lt;/<span class="pl-ent">code</span>&gt; failed to match the void at the end. It then tried the next character in the pattern, &lt;<span class="pl-ent">code</span>&gt;<span class="pl-c1">&amp;quot;</span>&lt;/<span class="pl-ent">code</span>&gt;, which also failed to match the void. The engine then backstepped one place and tried the &lt;<span class="pl-ent">code</span>&gt;<span class="pl-c1">&amp;quot;</span>&lt;/<span class="pl-ent">code</span>&gt; again (with &lt;<span class="pl-ent">code</span>&gt;r&lt;/<span class="pl-ent">code</span>&gt;), which also failed. The engine continued to backstep until it reached the last quotation mark.&lt;/<span class="pl-ent">p</span>&gt;</td>

        <td id="LC414" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">&lt;<span class="pl-ent">h3</span>&gt;Sample 3: Finding matching weather stations by [similarity of ] name.&lt;/<span class="pl-ent">h3</span>&gt;</td>

      <tr>
        <td id="L415" class="blob-num js-line-number" data-line-number="415"></td>
        <td id="LC415" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">&lt;<span class="pl-ent">p</span>&gt;For this example, pretend we are merging weather-station datasets from a wide variety of sources. Ideally, we would like to automatically identify any stations that are duplicated between datasets, because the number of stations is huge (10’s of thousands). The problem is that there are slight differences in station coordinates information and names/spelling which make this difficult to automate. Below is an example of one such case, for a location on the western border of Thailand.&lt;/<span class="pl-ent">p</span>&gt;</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td id="L416" class="blob-num js-line-number" data-line-number="416"></td>
        <td id="LC416" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">&lt;<span class="pl-ent">pre</span> <span class="pl-e">class</span>=<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">&quot;</span>r<span class="pl-pds">&quot;</span></span>&gt;&lt;<span class="pl-ent">code</span>&gt;stations <span class="pl-c1">&amp;lt;</span>- c(<span class="pl-c1">&amp;quot;</span>may sod<span class="pl-c1">&amp;quot;</span>, <span class="pl-c1">&amp;quot;</span>mae sot/tak<span class="pl-c1">&amp;quot;</span>, <span class="pl-c1">&amp;quot;</span>mae-sot<span class="pl-c1">&amp;quot;</span>, <span class="pl-c1">&amp;quot;</span>mae sot Thailand<span class="pl-c1">&amp;quot;</span>, <span class="pl-c1">&amp;quot;</span>ban-mae-sot<span class="pl-c1">&amp;quot;</span>, &#39;MAE SOD   / MYAWADDY&#39;, &#39;Bangkok Thailand&#39;)&lt;/<span class="pl-ent">code</span>&gt;&lt;/<span class="pl-ent">pre</span>&gt;</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td id="L417" class="blob-num js-line-number" data-line-number="417"></td>
        <td id="LC417" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">&lt;<span class="pl-ent">p</span>&gt;Lets suppose that these station locations are far enough apart that we do not automatically merge them based on location. A human can easily tell that these names are the same ( ‘ban’ means ‘town’ in Thai), but a computer has a harder time. The first thing we want to do is remove any special characters or capitalizations to make each string as standard as possible. &lt;<span class="pl-ent">code</span>&gt;gsub&lt;/<span class="pl-ent">code</span>&gt; will help with this.&lt;/<span class="pl-ent">p</span>&gt;</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td id="L418" class="blob-num js-line-number" data-line-number="418"></td>
        <td id="LC418" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">&lt;<span class="pl-ent">pre</span> <span class="pl-e">class</span>=<span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">&quot;</span>r<span class="pl-pds">&quot;</span></span>&gt;&lt;<span class="pl-ent">code</span>&gt;  n <span class="pl-c1">&amp;lt;</span>- tolower(stations) # make all lower case</td>
      </tr>

        <td id="LC419" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">( n <span class="pl-c1">&amp;lt;</span>- gsub(&#39;[-./ ]&#39;,&#39;&#39;, n))&lt;/<span class="pl-ent">code</span>&gt;&lt;/<span class="pl-ent">pre</span>&gt;</td>

        <td id="LC440" class="blob-code blob-code-inner js-file-line">&lt;<span class="pl-ent">p</span>&gt;There is a problem with at least two stations, named ‘maesodmyawaddy’ (originally ‘MAE SOD / MYAWADDY’) and ‘maysod’, for which none of the other pattern names match. Lets see if we can fix this with agrep, which uses a more flexible matching criteria.&lt;/<span class="pl-ent">p</span>&gt;</td>

        <td id="L441" class="blob-num js-line-number" data-line-number="441"></td>
